# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: social-engineering-awareness
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] A **data breach**, also known as **data leakage**, is "the unauthorized exposure, disclosure, or loss of personal information".
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Attackers have a variety of motives, from financial gain to political activism, political repression, and espionage.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Although prevention efforts can reduce the risk of a data breach, they cannot eliminate it.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] A large number of data breaches are never detected.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] If a breach becomes known to the company holding the data, post-breach efforts commonly include containing the breach, investigating its scope and cause, and notifications to people whose records were compromised, as required by law in many jurisdictions.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Law enforcement agencies may investigate breaches, although the hackers responsible are rarely caught.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Criminals often sell data obtained in breaches on the dark web.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Thus, people whose personal data was compromised are at elevated risk of identity theft for years afterwards and a significant number will become victims of this crime.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Data breach notification laws in many jurisdictions, including all states of the United States and European Union member states, require the notification of people whose data has been breached.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Lawsuits against the company that was breached are common, although few victims receive money from them.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] There is little empirical evidence of economic harm to firms from breaches except the direct cost, although there is some evidence suggesting a temporary, short-term decline in stock price.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Like almost all terms in cyber security, the definition of "data breach" is context-dependent.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Before the widespread adoption of data breach notification laws around 2005, the prevalence of data breaches is difficult to determine.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Even afterwards, annual statistics may be unreliable because breaches are sometimes reported years after they occur, or not reported at all.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Nevertheless, the statistics show a continued increase in the number and severity of data breaches that continues as of 2022.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] In 2016, researcher Sasha Romanosky estimated that data breaches (excluding phishing) outnumbered other security breaches by a factor of four.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] According to a 2020 estimate, 55 percent of data breaches were caused by organized crime, 10 percent by system administrators, 10 percent by end users such as customers or employees, and 10 percent by states or state-affiliated actors.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Opportunistic criminals may cause data breaches—often using malware or social engineering attacks, but they will typically move on if the security is above average.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] More organized criminals have more resources and are more focused in their targeting of particular data.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Both groups sell the information they obtain for financial gain.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Another source of data breaches are politically motivated hackers, for example Anonymous, that target particular objectives.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] State-sponsored hackers target either citizens of their country or foreign entities, for such purposes as political repression and espionage.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Often they use undisclosed zero-day vulnerabilities for which the hackers are paid large sums of money.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Despite developers' goal of delivering a product that works entirely as intended, virtually all software and hardware contains bugs.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] If a bug creates a security risk, it is called a vulnerability.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Patches are often released to fix identified vulnerabilities, but those that remain unknown (zero days) as well as those that have not been patched are still liable for exploitation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Both software written by the target of the breach and third party software used by them are vulnerable to attack.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The software vendor is rarely legally liable for the cost of breaches, thus creating an incentive to make cheaper but less secure software.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Vulnerabilities vary in their ability to be exploited by malicious actors.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The most valuable allow the attacker to inject and run their own code (called malware), without the user being aware of it.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Some malware is downloaded by users via clicking on a malicious link, but it is also possible for malicious web applications to download malware just from visiting the website (drive-by download).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Keyloggers, a type of malware that records a user's keystrokes, are often used in data breaches.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Hashing is also a good solution for keeping passwords safe from brute-force attacks, but only if the algorithm is sufficiently secure.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Many data breaches occur on the hardware operated by a partner of the organization targeted—including the 2013 Target data breach and 2014 JPMorgan Chase data breach.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Outsourcing work to a third party leads to a risk of data breach if that company has lower security standards; in particular, small companies often lack the resources to take as many security precautions.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] As a result, outsourcing agreements often include security guarantees and provisions for what happens in the event of a data breach.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Human causes of breaches often involve misplaced trust in a malicious actor.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Social engineering attacks rely on tricking an insider into doing something that compromises the system's security, such as revealing a password or clicking a link to download malware.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Data breaches may also be deliberately caused by insiders.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] One type of social engineering, phishing, obtains a user's credentials by sending them a malicious message impersonating a legitimate entity, such as a bank, and getting the user to enter their credentials onto a malicious website controlled by the cybercriminal.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Two-factor authentication can prevent the malicious actor from using the credentials.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Training employees to recognize social engineering is another common strategy.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Another source of breaches is accidental disclosure of information, for example publishing information that should be kept private.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] With the increase in remote work and bring your own device policies, large amounts of corporate data is stored on personal devices of employees.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Via carelessness or disregard of company security policies, these devices can be lost or stolen.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Technical solutions can prevent many causes of human error, such as encrypting all sensitive data, preventing employees from using insecure passwords, installing antivirus software to prevent malware, and implementing a robust patching system to ensure that all devices are kept up to date.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Although attention to security can reduce the risk of data breach, it cannot bring it to zero.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Security is not the only priority of organizations, and an attempt to achieve perfect security would make the technology unusable.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Many companies hire a chief information security officer (CISO) to oversee the company's information security strategy.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] To obtain information about potential threats, security professionals will network with each other and share information with other organizations facing similar threats.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Defense measures can include an updated incident response strategy, contracts with digital forensics firms that could investigate a breach, cyber insurance, and monitoring the dark web for stolen credentials of employees.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] In 2024, the United States' National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued a special publication, "Data Confidentiality: Identifying and Protecting Assets Against Data Breaches".
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The NIST Cybersecurity Framework also contains information about data protection.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Other organizations have released different standards for data protection.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The architecture of a company's systems plays a key role in deterring attackers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Daswani and Elbayadi recommend having only one means of authentication, avoiding redundant systems, and making the most secure setting default.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Defense in depth and distributed privilege—requiring multiple authentications to perform an operation—can make systems more difficult to compromise.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Giving employees and software the least amount of access necessary to fulfill their functions (principle of least privilege) limits the likelihood and damage of breaches.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Several data breaches were enabled by reliance on security by obscurity; the victims had put access credentials in publicly accessible files.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Nevertheless, prioritizing ease of use is also important because otherwise users might circumvent the security systems.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Rigorous software testing, including penetration testing, can reduce software vulnerabilities, and must be performed prior to each release even if the company is using a continuous integration/continuous deployment model where new versions are constantly being rolled out.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The principle of least persistence—avoiding the collection of data that is not necessary and destruction of data that is no longer necessary—can mitigate the harm from breaches.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The challenge is that destroying data can be more complex with modern database systems.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Of those that are, most breaches are detected by third parties; others are detected by employees or automated systems.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Responding to breaches is often the responsibility of a dedicated computer security incident response team, often including technical experts, public relations, and legal counsel.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Many companies do not have sufficient expertise in-house, and subcontract some of these roles; often, these outside resources are provided by the cyber insurance policy.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] After a data breach becomes known to the company, the next steps typically include confirming it occurred, notifying the response team, and attempting to contain the damage.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] To stop exfiltration of data, common strategies include shutting down affected servers, taking them offline, patching the vulnerability, and rebuilding.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Once the exact way that the data was compromised is identified, there is typically only one or two technical vulnerabilities that need to be addressed in order to contain the breach and prevent it from reoccurring.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] A penetration test can then verify that the fix is working as expected.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] If malware is involved, the organization must investigate and close all infiltration and exfiltration vectors, as well as locate and remove all malware from its systems.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] If data was posted on the dark web, companies may attempt to have it taken down.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Containing the breach can compromise investigation, and some tactics (such as shutting down servers) can violate the company's contractual obligations.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Gathering data about the breach can facilitate later litigation or criminal prosecution, but only if the data is gathered according to legal standards and the chain of custody is maintained.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Database forensics can narrow down the records involved, limiting the scope of the incident.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Extensive investigation may be undertaken, which can be even more expensive than litigation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] In the United States, breaches may be investigated by government agencies such as the Office for Civil Rights, the United States Department of Health and Human Services, and the Federal Trade Commission (FTC).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Law enforcement agencies may investigate breaches although the hackers responsible are rarely caught.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Notifications are typically sent out as required by law.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Many companies offer free credit monitoring to people affected by a data breach, although only around 5 percent of those eligible take advantage of the service.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Issuing new credit cards to consumers, although expensive, is an effective strategy to reduce the risk of credit card fraud.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Companies try to restore trust in their business operations and take steps to prevent a breach from reoccurring.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] After a data breach, criminals make money by selling data, such as usernames, passwords, social media or customer loyalty account information, debit and credit card numbers, and personal health information (see medical data breach).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Criminals often sell this data on the dark web—parts of the internet where it is difficult to trace users and illicit activity is widespread—using platforms like .onion or I2P.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Originating in the 2000s, the dark web, followed by untraceable cryptocurrencies such as Bitcoin in the 2010s, made it possible for criminals to sell data obtained in breaches with minimal risk of getting caught, facilitating an increase in hacking.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] One popular darknet marketplace, Silk Road, was shut down in 2013 and its operators arrested, but several other marketplaces emerged in its place.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Telegram is also a popular forum for illegal sales of data.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] When leaked databases contain full Social Security numbers and dates of birth, the exposed individuals face a heightened long-term risk of identity theft.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] This information may be used for a variety of purposes, such as spamming, obtaining products with a victim's loyalty or payment information, identity theft, prescription drug fraud, or insurance fraud.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The threat of data breach or revealing information obtained in a data breach can be used for extortion.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Consumers may suffer various forms of tangible or intangible harm from the theft of their personal data, or not notice any harm.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] A significant portion of those affected by a data breach become victims of identity theft.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] A person's identifying information often circulates on the dark web for years, causing an increased risk of identity theft regardless of remediation efforts.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Even if a customer does not end up footing the bill for credit card fraud or identity theft, they have to spend time resolving the situation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Intangible harms include doxxing (publicly revealing someone's personal information), for example medication usage or personal photos.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Impacts on the company can range from lost business, reduced employee productivity due to systems being offline or personnel redirected to working on the breach, resignation or firing of senior executives, reputational damage, and increasing the future cost of auditing or security.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] There is some evidence suggesting a temporary, short-term decline in stock price.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Consumer losses from a breach are usually a negative externality for the business.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Some experts have argued that the evidence suggests there is not enough direct costs or reputational damage from data breaches to sufficiently incentivize their prevention.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Estimating the cost of data breaches is difficult, both because not all breaches are reported and also because calculating the impact of breaches in financial terms is not straightforward.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] There are multiple ways of calculating the cost to businesses, especially when it comes to personnel time dedicated to dealing with the breach.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Author Kevvie Fowler estimates that more than half the direct cost incurred by companies is in the form of litigation expenses and services provided to affected individuals, with the remaining cost split between notification and detection, including forensics and investigation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] He argues that these costs are reduced if the organization has invested in security prior to the breach or has previous experience with breaches.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The more data records involved, the more expensive a breach typically will be.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] In 2016, researcher Sasha Romanosky estimated that while the mean breach cost around the targeted firm $5 million, this figure was inflated by a few highly expensive breaches, and the typical data breach was much less costly, around $200,000.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Romanosky estimated the total annual cost to corporations in the United States to be around $10 billion.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] It was estimated a 2025 data breach at cryptocurrency exchange Coinbase lead to as much as $400 million in total loss including damage to customers, a ransom demanded by hackers, legal costs, lost crypto assets, reputational fallout, and compliance.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The law regarding data breaches is often found in legislation to protect privacy more generally, and is dominated by provisions mandating notification when breaches occur.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Laws differ in how breaches are defined, what type of information is protected, the deadline for notification, and who has standing to sue if the law is violated.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Notification laws increase transparency and provide a reputational incentive for companies to reduce breaches.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The cost of notifying the breach can be high if many people were affected and is incurred regardless of the company's responsibility, so it can function like a strict liability fine.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] In healthcare, the HIPAA Breach Notification Rule, enacted as part of the HITECH Act in 2009, requires covered entities and business associates to notify affected individuals within 60 days of discovering a breach of unsecured protected health information (PHI).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Breaches affecting 500 or more individuals must also be reported to the Office for Civil Rights (OCR) and to prominent media outlets, and are posted publicly on the HHS Breach Portal, informally known as the "Wall of Shame".
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The February 2024 Change Healthcare cyberattack, which exposed the data of approximately 100 million individuals, highlighted the scale of healthcare data breach risks and led to increased scrutiny of cybersecurity practices across the healthcare sector.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] As of 2024, *Thomas on Data Breach* listed 62 United Nations member states that are covered by data breach notification laws.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Some other countries require breach notification in more general data protection laws.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Shortly after the first reported data breach in April 2002, California passed a law requiring notification when an individual's personal information was breached.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] In the United States, notification laws proliferated after the February 2005 ChoicePoint data breach, widely publicized in part because of the large number of people affected (more than 140,000) and also because of outrage that the company initially informed only affected people in California.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] In 2018, the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) took effect.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The GDPR requires notification within 72 hours, with very high fines possible for large companies not in compliance.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] This regulation also stimulated the tightening of data privacy laws elsewhere.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] As of 2022, the only United States federal law requiring notification for data breaches is limited to medical data regulated under HIPAA, but all 50 states (since Alabama passed a law in 2018) have their own general data breach notification laws.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Measures to protect data from a breach are typically absent from the law or vague.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Filling this gap is standards required by cyber insurance, which is held by most large companies and functions as *de facto* regulation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Of the laws that do exist, there are two main approaches—one that prescribes specific standards to follow, and the reasonableness approach.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The former is rarely used due to a lack of flexibility and reluctance of legislators to arbitrate technical issues; with the latter approach, the law is vague but specific standards can emerge from case law.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Companies often prefer the standards approach for providing greater legal certainty, but they might check all the boxes without providing a secure product.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] An additional flaw is that the laws are poorly enforced, with penalties often much less than the cost of a breach, and many companies do not follow them.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Many class-action lawsuits, derivative suits, and other litigation have been brought after data breaches.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] They are often settled regardless of the merits of the case due to the high cost of litigation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Even if a settlement is paid, few affected consumers receive any money as it usually is only cents to a few dollars per victim.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] Solove and Woodrow Hartzog argue that "Litigation has increased the costs of data breaches but has accomplished little else." Plaintiffs often struggle to prove that they suffered harm from a data breach.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] The contribution of a company's actions to a data breach varies, and likewise the liability for the damage resulting for data breaches is a contested matter.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/data-breach] It is disputed what standard should be applied, whether it is strict liability, negligence, or something else.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The term "phishing" was first recorded in 1995 in the cracking toolkit AOHell, but may have been used earlier in the hacker magazine *2600*.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] It is a variation of *fishing* and refers to the use of lures to "fish" for sensitive information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Measures to prevent or reduce the impact of phishing attacks include legislation, user education, public awareness, and technical security measures.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The importance of phishing awareness has increased in both personal and professional settings, with phishing attacks among businesses rising from 72% in 2017 to 86% in 2020, and reaching 94% in 2023.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Phishing techniques and vectors include email spam, vishing (voice phishing), targeted phishing (spear phishing, whaling), smishing (SMS), quishing (QR code), cross-site scripting, and MiTM 2FA attacks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Research literature identifies phishing as a persistent and evolving cybersecurity threat, with attacks increasingly incorporating advanced techniques such as automation and machine learning.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Phishing attacks, often delivered via email, attempt to trick individuals into giving away sensitive information or login credentials.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Most attacks are "bulk attacks" that are not targeted and are instead sent in bulk to a wide audience.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The goal of the attacker can vary, with common targets including financial institutions, email and cloud productivity providers, and streaming services.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The stolen information or access may be used to steal money, install malware, or spear phish others within the target organization.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Compromised streaming service accounts may also be sold on darknet markets.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] This type of social engineering attack can involve sending fraudulent emails or messages that appear to be from a trusted source, such as a bank or government agency.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These messages typically redirect to a fake login page where users are prompted to enter their credentials.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In many cases, these messages are designed to create urgency or trust by imitating legitimate communications, encouraging victims to disclose sensitive information such as login credentials or financial details.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Spear phishing attacks are often more effective than general phishing attempts because they are tailored to specific individuals and leverage personal or organizational information to increase credibility and success rates.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These attacks often target executives or those in financial departments with access to sensitive financial data and services.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Spear phishing often employs multiple communication methods at the same time including email, SMS, and calls to create a false sense of urgency.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Accountancy and audit firms are particularly vulnerable to spear phishing due to the value of the information their employees have access to.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The Russian government-run Threat Group-4127 (Fancy Bear; GRU Unit 26165) targeted Hillary Clinton's 2016 presidential campaign with spear phishing attacks on over 1,800 Google accounts, using the accounts-google.com domain to threaten targeted users.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] A study on spear phishing susceptibility among different age groups found that 43% of youth aged 18–25 years and 58% of older users clicked on simulated phishing links in daily e‑mails over 21 days.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Older women had the highest susceptibility, which declined among young users during the study but remained stable among older individuals.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Voice over IP (VoIP) is used in vishing or voice phishing attacks, where attackers make automated phone calls to large numbers of people, often using text-to-speech synthesizers, claiming fraudulent activity on their accounts.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The attackers spoof the calling phone number to appear as if it is coming from a legitimate bank or institution.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The victim is then prompted to enter sensitive information or connected to a live person who uses social engineering tactics to obtain information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Vishing takes advantage of the public's lower awareness and trust in voice telephony compared to email phishing.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] SMS phishing or smishing is a phishing attack using mobile text messages to deliver bait messages.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The victim is usually asked to click a link, call a phone number, or contact an email address provided by the attacker.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] They may be asked to provide private information, such as login credentials.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Attackers may pretend to be government officers, customer support, shippers, colleague, boss, or a wrong number.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The range of possibilities requires permanent vigilance and critical thinking to detect attacks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Smishing messages may be identified when they come from unusual phone numbers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The difficulty in identifying illegitimate links can be compounded on mobile devices due to the limited display of URLs in mobile browsers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These kinds of scams apply various forms of social engineering including scammers that pretend to be financial institutions or customer service.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Page hijacking involves redirecting users to malicious websites or exploit kits by compromising legitimate web pages, often using cross site scripting.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Hackers may insert exploit kits such as MPack into compromised websites to exploit legitimate users visiting the server.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Page hijacking can also involve insertion of malicious inline frames, allowing exploit kits to load.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] This tactic is often used together with watering hole attacks on corporate targets.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In "quishing" (QR code phishing), scammers exploit the convenience of QR codes to trick users into giving up sensitive data, by scanning a code containing an embedded malicious web site link.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Unlike traditional phishing, which relies on deceptive links in emails or websites, quishing uses QR codes to bypass email filters and appear less suspicious, as victims may not scrutinize them as carefully as URLs.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The bogus codes may be sent by email, social media, or hard copy stickers placed over legitimate QR codes on such as on advertisements or car park notices.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] When victims scan a code, they may be redirected to a fake website designed to steal personal information, login credentials, or financial details.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] As QR codes become more widely used for things like payments, event check-ins, and product information, quishing is emerging as a significant concern for digital security.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Cybercriminals can also merge QR Code phishing with Browser-in-The-Browser (BiTB) to trick users into approving the attacker's two-factor access.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These trends indicate the growing sophistication of quishing tactics .
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Users are advised to exercise caution when scanning unfamiliar QR codes and ensure they are from trusted sources, although the UK's National Cyber Security Centre rates the risk as lower than other types of lure.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Traditional phishing attacks are typically limited to capturing user credentials directly inputted into fraudulent websites.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] However, the advent of Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) phishing techniques has significantly advanced the sophistication of these attacks, enabling cybercriminals to bypass two-factor authentication (2FA) mechanisms during a user's active session on a web service.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] MitM phishing attacks employ intermediary tools that intercept communication between the user and the legitimate service.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Evilginx, originally created as an open-source tool for penetration testing and ethical hacking, has been repurposed by cybercriminals for MitM attacks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Evilginx works like a middleman, passing information between the victim and the real website without saving passwords or login codes.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] This makes it harder for security systems to detect, since they usually look for phishing sites that store stolen data.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] By grabbing login tokens and session cookies instantly, attackers can break into accounts and use them just like the real user, for as long as the session stays active.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Attackers employ various methods, including phishing emails, social engineering tactics, or distributing malicious links via social media platforms.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Once the victim interacts with the counterfeit site, the MitM tool intercepts the authentication process, effectively bypassing 2FA protections.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Phishing attacks often involve creating fake links that appear to be from a legitimate organization.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These links may use misspelled URLs or subdomains to deceive the user.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Another tactic is to make the link's displayed text appear trustworthy, while actually linking to the phisher's site.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] To check the destination of a link, many email clients and web browsers show the URL in the status bar when the mouse is hovering over it.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] However, some phishers may be able to bypass this security measure.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Internationalized domain names (IDNs) can be exploited via IDN spoofing or homograph attacks to allow attackers to create fake websites with visually identical addresses to legitimate ones.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These attacks have been used by phishers to disguise malicious URLs using open URL redirectors on trusted websites.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] An example of this is in `http://www.exаmple.com/`, where the third character is not the Latin letter 'a', but instead the Cyrillic character 'а'.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] When the victim uses the link, unaware of the replaced letter, they get redirected to the malicious site `http://www.xn--exmple-4nf.com/`.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Phishing often uses social engineering techniques to trick users into performing actions such as clicking a link or opening an attachment, or revealing sensitive information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] It often involves pretending to be a trusted entity and creating a sense of urgency, like threatening to close or seize a victim's bank or insurance account.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] An alternative technique to impersonation-based phishing is the use of fake news articles to trick victims into clicking on a malicious link.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These links often lead to fake websites that appear legitimate, but are actually run by attackers who may try to install malware or present fake "virus" notifications to the victim.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] A major concern in contemporary contexts is the potential for Generative AI to exacerbate phishing and social engineering.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] AI generation for both texts and images improves the realism in visual content, leading to more connective forms of manipulating.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] They also strengthen the attackers ability to target their victims and ease automation processes that enhance the attacks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Early phishing techniques can be traced back to the 1990s, when black hat hackers and the warez community used AOL to steal credit card information and commit other online crimes.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The term "phishing" is said to have been coined by Khan C.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Smith, a well-known spammer and hacker, and its first recorded mention was found in the hacking tool AOHell, which was released in 1994.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] AOHell allowed hackers to impersonate AOL staff and send instant messages to victims asking them to reveal their passwords.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In response, AOL implemented measures to prevent phishing and eventually shut down the warez scene on their platform.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In the 2000s, phishing attacks became more organized and targeted.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The first known direct attempt against a payment system, E-gold, occurred in June 2001, and shortly after the September 11 attacks, a "post-9/11 id check" phishing attack followed.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The first known phishing attack against a retail bank was reported in September 2003.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Between May 2004 and May 2005, approximately 1.2 million computer users in the United States suffered losses caused by phishing, totaling approximately US$929 million.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Phishing was recognized as a fully organized part of the black market, and specializations emerged on a global scale that provided phishing software for payment, which were assembled and implemented into phishing campaigns by organized gangs.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The United Kingdom banking sector suffered from phishing attacks, with losses from web banking fraud almost doubling in 2005 compared to 2004.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In 2006, almost half of phishing thefts were committed by groups operating through the Russian Business Network based in St.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Email scams posing as the Internal Revenue Service were also used to steal sensitive data from U.S. taxpayers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Social networking sites are a prime target of phishing, since the personal details in such sites can be used in identity theft; In 2007, 3.6 million adults lost US$3.2 billion due to phishing attacks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The Anti-Phishing Working Group reported receiving 115,370 phishing email reports from consumers with US and China hosting more than 25% of the phishing pages each in the third quarter of 2009.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Phishing in the 2010s saw a significant increase in the number of attacks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In 2011, the master keys for RSA SecurID security tokens were stolen through a phishing attack.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Chinese phishing campaigns also targeted high-ranking officials in the US and South Korean governments and military, as well as Chinese political activists.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] According to Ghosh, phishing attacks increased from 187,203 in 2010 to 445,004 in 2012.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In August 2013, Outbrain suffered a spear-phishing attack, and in November 2013, 110 million customer and credit card records were stolen from Target customers through a phished subcontractor account. subsequently, CEO and IT security staff were dismissed.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In August 2014, iCloud leaks of celebrity photos were based on phishing e-mails sent to victims that looked like they came from Apple or Google.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In November 2014, phishing attacks on ICANN gained administrative access to the Centralized Zone Data System; also gained was data about users in the system - and access to ICANN's public Governmental Advisory Committee wiki, blog, and whois information portal.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Fancy Bear was linked to spear-phishing attacks against the Pentagon email system in August 2015, and the group used a zero-day exploit of Java in a spear-phishing attack on the White House and NATO.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Fancy Bear carried out spear phishing attacks on email addresses associated with the Democratic National Committee in the first quarter of 2016.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In August 2016, members of the Bundestag and political parties such as Linken-faction leader Sahra Wagenknecht, Junge Union, and the CDU of Saarland were targeted by spear-phishing attacks suspected to be carried out by Fancy Bear.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In August 2016, the World Anti-Doping Agency reported the receipt of phishing emails sent to users of its database claiming to be official WADA, but consistent with the Russian hacking group Fancy Bear.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In 2017, 76% of organizations experienced phishing attacks, with nearly half of the information security professionals surveyed reporting an increase from 2016.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In the first half of 2017, businesses and residents of Qatar were hit with over 93,570 phishing events in a three-month span.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In August 2017, customers of Amazon faced the Amazon Prime Day phishing attack, when hackers sent out seemingly legitimate deals to customers of Amazon.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] When Amazon's customers attempted to make purchases using the "deals", the transaction would not be completed, prompting the retailer's customers to input data that could be compromised and stolen.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In 2018, the company block.one, which developed the EOS.IO blockchain, was attacked by a phishing group who sent phishing emails to all customers aimed at intercepting the user's cryptocurrency wallet key, and a later attack targeted airdrop tokens.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Phishing attacks have evolved in the 2020s to include elements of social engineering, as demonstrated by the July 15, 2020, Twitter breach.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In this case, a 17-year-old hacker and accomplices set up a fake website resembling Twitter's internal VPN provider used by remote working employees.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Posing as helpdesk staff, they called multiple Twitter employees, directing them to submit their credentials to the fake VPN website.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Using the details supplied by the unsuspecting employees, they were able to seize control of several high-profile user accounts, including those of Barack Obama, Elon Musk, Joe Biden, and Apple Inc.'s company account.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The hackers then sent messages to Twitter followers soliciting Bitcoin, promising to double the transaction value in return.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The hackers collected 12.86 BTC (about $117,000 at the time).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In the 2020s, phishing as a service (PhaaS) platforms like Darcula allow attackers to easily fake trusted websites.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] There are anti-phishing websites which publish exact messages that have been recently circulating the internet, such as FraudWatch International and Millersmiles.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Such sites often provide specific details about the particular messages.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] As recently as 2007, the adoption of anti-phishing strategies by businesses needing to protect personal and financial information was low.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] There are several different techniques to combat phishing, including legislation and technology created specifically to protect against phishing.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These techniques include steps that can be taken by individuals, as well as by organizations.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Phone, web site, and email phishing can now be reported to authorities, as described below.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Effective phishing education, including conceptual knowledge and feedback, is an important part of any organization's anti-phishing strategy.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] While there is limited data on the effectiveness of education in reducing susceptibility to phishing, much information on the threat is available online.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Simulated phishing campaigns, in which organizations test their employees' training by sending fake phishing emails, are commonly used to assess their effectiveness.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] One example is a study by the National Library of Medicine, in which an organization received 858,200 emails during a 1-month testing period, with 139,400 (16%) being marketing and 18,871 (2%) being identified as potential threats.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These campaigns are often used in the healthcare industry, as healthcare data is a valuable target for hackers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These campaigns are just one of the ways that organizations are working to combat phishing.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Nearly all legitimate e-mail messages from companies to their customers contain an item of information that is not readily available to phishers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Some companies, for example PayPal, always address their customers by their username in emails, so if an email addresses the recipient in a generic fashion ("Dear PayPal customer") it is likely to be an attempt at phishing.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Furthermore, PayPal offers various methods to determine spoof emails and advises users to forward suspicious emails to their spoof@PayPal.com domain to investigate and warn other customers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Emails from banks and credit card companies often include partial account numbers, but research has shown that people tend to not differentiate between the first and last digits.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] A study on phishing attacks in game environments found that educational games can effectively educate players against information disclosures and can increase awareness on phishing risk thus mitigating risks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The Anti-Phishing Working Group, one of the largest anti-phishing organizations in the world, produces regular report on trends in phishing attacks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] A wide range of technical approaches are available to prevent phishing attacks reaching users or to prevent them from successfully capturing sensitive information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Specialized spam filters can reduce the number of phishing emails that reach their addressees' inboxes.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These filters use a number of techniques including machine learning and natural language processing approaches to classify phishing emails, and reject email with forged addresses.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Another popular approach to fighting phishing is to maintain a list of known malicious sites and verify URLs against that list in real time.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These browsers often source their intelligence through trusted security partners or specialized browser extensions, such as Google Safe Browsing, Microsoft Defender Smartscreen, Bitdefender TrafficLight, uBlock Origin Lite, Netcraft Extension and Blue Arca PhishGuard.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Web browsers such as Google Chrome, Microsoft Edge, Mozilla Firefox, Safari, and Opera all contain this type of anti-phishing measure.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Firefox 2 used Google anti-phishing software.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Opera 9.1 uses live blacklists from Phishtank, cyscon and GeoTrust, as well as live whitelists from GeoTrust.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Some implementations of this approach send the visited URLs to a central service to be checked, which has raised concerns about privacy.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] According to a 2026 study by AV-Comparatives, Avast Secure Browser and Norton Security Browser were found to be most effective at detecting fraudulent sites, blocking 94% of phishing URLs, while Google Chrome blocked 72%.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] An approach introduced in mid-2006 involves switching to a special DNS service that filters out known phishing domains.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] To mitigate the problem of phishing sites impersonating a victim site by embedding its images (such as logos), several site owners have altered the images to send a message to the visitor that a site may be fraudulent.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The image may be moved to a new filename and the original permanently replaced, or a server can detect that the image was not requested as part of normal browsing, and instead send a warning image.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The Bank of America website was one of several that asked users to select a personal image (marketed as SiteKey) and displayed this user-selected image with any forms that request a password.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Users of the bank's online services were instructed to enter a password only when they saw the image they selected.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The bank has since discontinued the use of SiteKey.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Several studies suggest that few users refrain from entering their passwords when images are absent.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In addition, this feature (like other forms of two-factor authentication) is susceptible to other attacks, such as those suffered by Scandinavian bank Nordea in late 2005, and Citibank in 2006.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] A similar system, in which an automatically generated "Identity Cue" consisting of a colored word within a colored box is displayed to each website user, is in use at other financial institutions.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Security skins are a related technique that involves overlaying a user-selected image onto the login form as a visual cue that the form is legitimate.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Unlike the website-based image schemes, however, the image itself is shared only between the user and the browser, and not between the user and the website.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The scheme also relies on a mutual authentication protocol, which makes it less vulnerable to attacks that affect user-only authentication schemes.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Still another technique relies on a dynamic grid of images that is different for each login attempt.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The user must identify the pictures that fit their pre-chosen categories (such as dogs, cars and flowers).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Only after they have correctly identified the pictures that fit their categories are they allowed to enter their alphanumeric password to complete the login.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Several companies offer digital risk protection (DRP) services to detect, block, and take down malicious websites, social accounts, applications, and digital infrastructure impersonating legitimate organizations.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] While early tools required extensive manual oversight, modern vendors like Netcraft, ZeroFox and Recorded Future have moved toward higher levels of automation to combat the speed of AI-driven phishing.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Individuals can contribute by reporting phishing to both volunteer and industry groups, such as cyscon or PhishTank.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Phishing web pages and emails can be reported to Google.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Organizations can implement two factor or multi-factor authentication (MFA), which requires a user to use at least 2 factors when logging in.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] (For example, a user must both present a smart card and a password).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] This mitigates some risk, in the event of a successful phishing attack, the stolen password on its own cannot be reused to further breach the protected system.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] However, there are several attack methods which can defeat many of the typical systems.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] MFA schemes such as WebAuthn address this issue by design.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Federal Trade Commission filed the first phishing lawsuit, against a Californian teenager suspected of creating a webpage mimicking America Online and stealing credit card information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Other countries have followed this lead by tracing and arresting phishers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] A phishing kingpin, Valdir Paulo de Almeida, was arrested in Brazil for leading one of the largest phishing crime rings, which in two years stole between US$18 million and US$37 million.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] UK authorities jailed two men in June 2005 for their role in a phishing scam, in a case connected to the U.S.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Secret Service Operation Firewall, which targeted notorious "carder" websites.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In 2006, Japanese police arrested eight people for creating fake Yahoo Japan websites, netting themselves ¥100 million (US$870,000) and the FBI detained a gang of sixteen in the U.S. and Europe in Operation Cardkeeper.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Senator Patrick Leahy introduced the Anti-Phishing Act of 2005 to Congress in the United States on March 1, 2005.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] This bill aimed to impose fines of up to $250,000 and prison sentences of up to five years on criminals who used fake websites and emails to defraud consumers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In the UK, the Fraud Act 2006 introduced a general offense of fraud punishable by up to ten years in prison and prohibited the development or possession of phishing kits with the intention of committing fraud.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Companies have also joined the effort to crack down on phishing.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] On March 31, 2005, Microsoft filed 117 federal lawsuits in the U.S.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] District Court for the Western District of Washington.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The lawsuits accuse "John Doe" defendants of obtaining passwords and confidential information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] March 2005 also saw a partnership between Microsoft and the Australian government teaching law enforcement officials how to combat various cyber crimes, including phishing.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Microsoft announced a planned further 100 lawsuits outside the U.S. in March 2006, followed by the commencement, as of November 2006, of 129 lawsuits mixing criminal and civil actions.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] AOL reinforced its efforts against phishing in early 2006 with three lawsuits seeking a total of US$18 million under the 2005 amendments to the Virginia Computer Crimes Act, and Earthlink has joined in by helping to identify six men subsequently charged with phishing fraud in Connecticut.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] In January 2007, Jeffrey Brett Goodin of California became the first defendant convicted by a jury under the provisions of the CAN-SPAM Act of 2003.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] He was found guilty of sending thousands of emails to AOL users, while posing as the company's billing department, which prompted customers to submit personal and credit card information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Facing a possible 101 years in prison for the CAN-SPAM violation and ten other counts including wire fraud, the unauthorized use of credit cards, and the misuse of AOL's trademark, he was sentenced to serve 70 months.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Goodin had been in custody since failing to appear for an earlier court hearing and began serving his prison term immediately.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Phishing is the leading cause of healthcare data breaches in the United States, with the U.S.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] Department of Health and Human Services Office for Civil Rights consistently identifying email-based attacks as the most common initial attack vector in breaches reported under the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Breach Notification Rule.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities to implement security awareness and training programs for their workforce, including training on procedures for guarding against and detecting malicious software and monitoring log-in attempts (45 CFR 164.308(a)(5)).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/phishing] These proposals were prompted in part by large-scale healthcare breaches initiated through phishing, including the 2024 Change Healthcare cyberattack that compromised the records of approximately 100 million individuals.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] A reason for pretexting's prevalence among social engineering attacks is its reliance on manipulating the human mind in order to gain access to the information the attacker wants, versus manipulating a technological system.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] When looking for victims, attackers can watch out for a variety of characteristics, such as ability to trust, low perception of threat, response to authority, and susceptibility to react with fear or excitement in different situations.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Throughout history, pretexting attacks have increased in complexity, having evolved from manipulating operators over the phone in the 1900s to the Hewlett Packard scandal in the 2000s, which involved the use of social security numbers, phones, and banks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Current education frameworks on social engineering are used in organizations, although researchers in academia have suggested possible improvements to those frameworks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Social engineering is a psychological manipulation tactic that leads to the unwilling or unknowing response of the target/victim.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] It is one of the top information security threats in the modern world, affecting organizations, business management, and industries.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Social engineering attacks are considered difficult to prevent due to its root in psychological manipulation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] These attacks can also reach a broader scale.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] In other security attacks, a company that holds customer data might be breached.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] With social engineering attacks, both the company (specifically workers within the company) and the customer directly are susceptible to being targeted.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] An example would be in the banking industry, where not only bank employees can be attacked, but the customers as well.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Social engineering culprits directly target customers or employees to work around trying to hack a purely technological system and exploit human vulnerabilities.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Though its definition in relation to cybersecurity has been skewed across different literature, a common theme is that social engineering (in cybersecurity) exploits human vulnerabilities in order to breach entities such as computers and information technology.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Social engineering has little literature and research done on it currently.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] However, a main part of the methodology when researching social engineering is to set up a made-up pretext.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] When assessing which social engineering attacks are the most dangerous or harmful, (e.g., phishing, vishing, water-holing), the type of pretext is a largely insignificant factor, seeing as some attacks can have multiple pretexts.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Thus, pretexting itself is widely used, not just as its own attack, but as a component of others.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] In cybersecurity, pretexting can be considered one of the earliest stages of evolution for social engineering.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] For example, while the social engineering attack known as phishing relies on modern items such as credit cards and mainly occurs in the electronic space, pretexting was and can be implemented without technology.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Pretexting was one of the first examples of social engineering.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Coined by the FBI in 1974, the concept of pretexting was often used to help in their investigations.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] In this phase, pretexting consisted of an attacker calling the victim simply asking for information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Pretexting attacks usually consist of persuasion tactics.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] After this beginning phase of social engineering's evolution (1974–83), pretexting changed from not only persuasion tactics, but deception tactics as well.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] As technology developed, pretexting methods developed alongside it.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Soon, hackers had access to a wider audience of victims due to the invention of social media.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Reverse social engineering is a more specific example of pretexting.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] It is a non-electronic form of social engineering where the attacker creates a pretext where the user is manipulated into contacting the attacker first, versus the other way around.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Typically, reverse engineering attacks involve the attacker advertising their services as a type of technical aid, establishing credibility.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Then, the victim is tricked into contacting the attacker after seeing advertisements, without the attacker directly contacting the victim in the first place.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Due to the connection between the attacker and the victim, the victim will be inclined to believe the attacker and click on the harmful link).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Pretexting was and continues to be seen as a useful tactic in social engineering attacks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] According to researchers, this is because they don't rely on technology (such as hacking into computer systems or breaching technology).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Pretexting can occur online, but it is more reliant on the user and the aspects of their personality the attacker can utilize to their advantage.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Attacks that are more reliant on the user are harder to track and control, as each person responds to social engineering and pretexting attacks differently.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Directly attacking a computer, however, can take less effort to solve, since computers relatively work in similar ways.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] There are certain characteristics of users that attackers pinpoint and target.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] If the victim is "prized", it means that one has some type of information that the social engineer desires.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Trustworthiness goes along with likability, as typically the more someone is liked, the more they are trusted.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Similarly, when trust is established between the social engineer (the attacker) and the victim, credibility is also established.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Thus, it is easier for the victim to divulge personal information to the attacker if the victim is more easily able to trust.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] How easily a person reacts to events and to what degree can be used in a social engineer's favor.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Particularly, emotions like excitement and fear are often used to persuade people to divulge information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] For example, a pretext could be established wherein the social engineer teases an exciting prize for the victim if they agree to give the social engineer their banking information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] The feeling of excitement can be used to lure the victim into the pretext and persuade them to give the attacker the information being sought after.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Despite understanding that threats exist when doing anything online, most people will perform actions that are against this, such as clicking on random links or accepting unknown friend requests.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] This is due to a person perceiving the action as having a low threat or negative consequence.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] This lack of fear/threat, despite an awareness of its presence, is another reason why social engineering attacks, especially pretexting, are prevalent.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] If the victim is submissive and compliant, then an attacker is more likely to be successful in the attack if a pretext is set where the victim thinks the attacker is posed as some type of authoritative figure.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] The October 1984 article *Switching centres and Operators* detailed a common pretexting attack at the time.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Attackers would often contact operators who specifically operated for deaf people using Teletypewriters.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] The logic was that these operators were often more patient than regular operators, so it was easier to manipulate and persuade them for the information the attacker desired.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] A notable example is the Hewlett Packard scandal.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] The company Hewlett Packard wanted to know who was leaking out information to journalists.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] In order to do so, they provided private investigators with employees' personal information (such as social security numbers), and the private investigators in turn called phone companies impersonating those employees in hopes of obtaining call records.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] When the scandal was discovered, the CEO resigned.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] In general, socialbots are machine-operated fake social media profiles employed by social engineering attackers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] On social media sites like Facebook, socialbots can be used to send mass friend requests in order to find as many potential victims as possible.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Using reverse social engineering techniques, attackers can use socialbots to gain massive amounts of private information on many social media users.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] In 2018, a fraudster impersonated entrepreneur Elon Musk on Twitter, altering their name and profile picture.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] They proceeded to initiate a deceptive giveaway scam, promising to multiply the cryptocurrency sent by users.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Subsequently, the scammer retained the funds sent to them.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] This incident serves as an example of how pretexting was employed as a tactic in a social engineering attack.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Current education frameworks on the topic of social engineering fall in between two categories: awareness and training.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Awareness is when the information about social engineering is presented to the intended party to inform them about the topic.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Training is specifically teaching necessary skills that people will learn and use in case they are in a social engineering attack or can encounter one.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Awareness and training can be combined into one intensive process when constructing education frameworks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] While research has been done on the successfulness and necessity of training programs in the context of cybersecurity education, up to 70% of information can be lost when it comes to social engineering training.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] In a research study on social engineering education in banks across the Asian Pacific, it was found that most frameworks only touched upon either awareness or training.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] Also, the only type of social engineering attack that was taught was phishing.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] By looking at and comparing the security policies on these banks' websites, the policies contain generalized language such as "malware" and "scams", while also missing the details behind the different types of social engineering attacks and examples of each one of those types.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] This generalization does not benefit the users being educated by these frameworks, as there is considerable depth missing when the user is only educated on broad terms like the examples above.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] As well, purely technical methods of combatting against social engineering and pretexting attacks, such as firewalls and antiviruses, are ineffective.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/pretexting] This is because social engineering attacks typically involve exploiting the social characteristic of human nature, thus purely combatting technology is ineffective.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] In psychology, **manipulation** is defined as an action designed to influence or control another person in an underhanded or subtle manner which facilitates one's personal aims.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Methods someone may use to manipulate another person may include seduction, suggestion, coercion, and blackmail.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Manipulation is generally considered a dishonest form of social influence as it is used at the expense of others.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Humans are inherently capable of manipulative and deceptive behavior, with the main differences being that of specific personality characteristics or disorders.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] By 1730, the word *manipulation* was used to refer to a method of digging ore.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The term derives from the French manipulation, which in turn comes from manipule, meaning "handful", a unit of measure used by pharmacists, later having a sense by 1828 of handling or managing people for one's own purposes.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Manipulation differs from general influence and persuasion.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Manipulation, unlike persuasion, typically involves exploiting the vulnerabilities of an individual.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Non-manipulative influence is generally perceived to be harmless and it is not seen as unduly coercive to the individual's right of acceptance or rejection of influence.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Persuasion is the ability to move others to a desired action, usually within the context of a specific goal.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Persuasion often attempts to influence a person's beliefs, religion, motivations, or behavior.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Influence and persuasion are neither viewed as positive nor negative, unlike manipulation which is viewed as negative.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] While the motivations for manipulation are mostly self-serving, certain styles of social influence can be intended to be to the benefit of others.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Manipulation can be defined as the use of strategies to further personal driven goals at the expense of others and is usually considered antisocial behavior.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Pro-social behavior is a voluntary act intended to help or benefit another individual or group of individuals and is an important part of empathy.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Manipulative behavior is fundamentally deliberate and intentional, with the manipulator knowing full well the consequences of their actions, and what they want out of the person being manipulated.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Different measures of manipulativeness focus on different aspects or expressions of manipulation and tend to paint slightly different pictures of its predictors.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Features such as low empathy, high narcissism, use of self-serving rationalizations, and an interpersonal style marked by high agency (dominance) and low communion (i.e. cold-heartedness) are consistent across measures.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] A study by Buss, et al. explored how individuals use manipulation to shape their environments to fit their personal characteristics.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Across two studies, researchers identified six main manipulation tactics: charm, silent treatment, coercion, reason, regression, and debasement.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] These tactics were consistent across different situations, with charm commonly used to initiate behavior and coercion or silent treatment used to stop it.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The use of these tactics was linked to personality traits such as Neuroticism, Extraversion, and Agreeableness, and was consistent across self-reports and observer ratings.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Twelve distinct manipulation tactics were identified through separate factor analyses of two instruments derived from different data sources.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] These included six tactics Charm, Reason, Coercion, Silent Treatment, Debasement, Regression, and six additional tactics: Responsibility Invocation, Reciprocity, Monetary Reward, Pleasure Induction, Social Comparison, and Hardball (the latter encompassing threats, deception, and aggression).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Personality traits were assessed using three sources of data: self-reports, spouse reports, and evaluations by independent interviewers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The findings revealed consistent associations between personality dimensions and manipulation strategies.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Specifically, Surgency was linked to Coercion and Responsibility Invocation; Desurgency to Debasement; Agreeableness to Pleasure Induction; Disagreeableness to Coercion; Conscientiousness to Reason; Emotional Instability to Regression; and Intellect-Openness to Reason.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] A family study of high-school students and their parents investigated the origin of individual differences in manipulation tactics.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The results indicated significant familial aggregation of manipulation tactics, as shown by parent–offspring correlations and midparent–offspring regressions.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] While manipulation tactics were linked to low Agreeableness and high Neuroticism from the Five-Factor Model, personality traits played a minor role in explaining their selection and use.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Manipulative behavior occurs in a variety of outlets, such as on the internet.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Researchers and pundits have expressed concern for the ability of technology to manipulate the opinions and actions of people.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Scholars have discussed the potential modern technologies have to affect the autonomy of an individual.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The concept has spawned an extensive literature within the field of psychology, and other disciplines interested in human behavior.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Cambridge Analytica was under scrutiny for collecting personal data belonging to millions of Facebook users for political advertising without informed consent.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Braiker identified the following ways that manipulators control their victims, with some of them including positive reinforcement, which includes praise, superficial charm, superficial sympathy (crocodile tears), excessive apologizing or forced laugh or smile.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] According to psychology author George K.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Simon, successful psychological manipulation primarily involves the manipulator: Simon states that manipulative individuals may use a variety of deceptive techniques to exert control or avoid accountability.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Methods include lying by commissioh, lying by omission, pretending to be in denial, rationalization, selective inattention/selective attention, and diversion.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Manipulativeness is a primary feature found in the Machiavellianism construct.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The MACH-IV, conceptualized by Richard Christie and Florence Geis, is a popular and widely used psychological measure of manipulative and deceptive behavior.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The emotional manipulation scale is a ten-item questionnaire developed in 2006 through factor analysis, primarily to measure one's tendency to use emotions to their advantage in controlling others.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] At the time of publication, emotional intelligence assessments did not specifically examine manipulative behavior and were instead predominantly focused on Big Five personality trait assessment.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The "Managing the Emotions of Others Scale" (MEOS) was developed in 2013 through factor analysis to measure the ability to change emotions of others.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The survey questions measure six categories: mood (or emotional state) enhancement, mood worsening, concealing emotions, capacity for inauthenticity, poor emotion skills, and using diversion to enhance mood.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The enhancement, worsening and diversion categories have been used to identify the ability and willingness of manipulative behavior.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The MEOS has also been used for assessing emotional intelligence, and has been compared to the HEXACO model of personality structure, for which the capacity for inauthenticity category in the MEOS was found to correspond to low honesty-humility scores on the HEXACO.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The dark triad *Dirty Dozen* and the Short Dark Triad (SD3 or simply D3) also measures a callous, manipulative, self oriented style.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] There are several measures that assess interpersonally manipulative characteristics.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Measures of psychopathy and narcissism have their own subscales that address manipulation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Other examples include the Honesty-Humility subscale on the HEXACO model of personality, the Agreeableness factor in the Big Five personality test, and on certain factors of the MMPI.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Manipulative behavior is cited as one factor contributing to the reluctance of some psychiatric professionals to work with individuals diagnosed with personality disorders (PDs).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Many times this behavior can elicit strong negative emotional reactions, potentially hindering effective care and treatment.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Manipulative tendencies may derive from cluster B personality disorders such as narcissistic personality disorder, antisocial personality disorder, and borderline personality disorder.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Manipulative behavior has also been related with one's level of emotional intelligence.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Discussion of manipulation may vary depending on which behavior is specifically included, and whether one is referring to the general population or in clinical contexts.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Under the ICD-11 classification of personality disorders, personality disorder is diagnosed dimensionally based on severity levels, with trait qualifiers providing additional specification in regards to how the pathology manifests itself.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] One of these is *Dissociality*, of which the aspect *lack of empathy* is characterized by deceitful, manipulative and exploitative behaviors.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Antisocial personality disorder features deceit and manipulation of others as an explicit criterion.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] This includes behaviors like lying and superficial displays of charisma to frequent use of aliases and disguises, and criminal fraudulence.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] The related syndrome of psychopathy also features pathological lying and manipulation for personal gain, as well as superficial charm, as cardinal features.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Paul Hofer interpreted manipulation to be a psychological defense in regards to those who are affected by their antisocial personality.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Paul Babiak views manipulation to be a core feature in how those with high psychopathic traits behave in the workplace.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Borderline personality disorder is unique in the grouping as "borderline" manipulation is characterized as unintentional and dysfunctional manipulation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Linehan has stated that people with borderline personality disorder often exhibit behaviors which are not truly manipulative, but are erroneously interpreted as such.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] According to Linehan, these behaviors often appear as unthinking manifestations of intense pain, and are often not deliberate as to be considered truly manipulative.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] In the DSM-5, manipulation was removed as a defining characteristic of borderline personality disorder.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Narcissistic personality disorder is characterized by a belief of superiority, exhibitionism, self-centeredness and a lack of empathy.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Individuals with NPD can be charming but also show exploitive behaviors in the interpersonal domain.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] They are motivated by success, beauty, and may have feelings of entitlement.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Those with this disorder often engage in assertive self enhancement and antagonistic self-protection.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Conduct disorder is the appearance of antisocial behavior occurring in children and adolescents.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Individuals with this disorder are characterized by a lack of empathy, a low sense of guilt, and shallow emotionality.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Aggression and violence are two factors that characterize individuals with this disorder.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] In order for a child to be diagnosed with this disorder, the behavior must be consistent for at least 12 months.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Factitious disorder is a mental illness in which individuals purposely fake having symptoms of some condition, physically or psychologically.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Fabricating illnesses allows individuals to feel a thrill and receive free aid in hospital admissions and treatment.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/psychological-manipulation] Feelings of persistence, abuse in early childhood, and excessive thoughts were common for these individuals who connected to Borderline Personality Disorder.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Employees' behavior, cognitive biases, and decision-making processes influence the effectiveness of security measures.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Research indicates that psychological factors, such as optimism bias, overconfidence, and habitual behaviors, can undermine security awareness initiatives.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] To address these challenges, organizations are increasingly using behavioral analytics and security nudges—subtle prompts like password reminders and phishing warnings—to encourage secure behavior.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Human error remains the leading cause of cybersecurity incidents.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] A 2023 IBM Security report found that 95% of breaches are due to human mistakes, including falling for phishing emails, using weak passwords, and mishandling sensitive data.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Organizations emphasize security awareness training as a key strategy to mitigate this risk.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] It is particularly important for leadership to foster a culture of cybersecurity and to provide targeted training to increase security awareness among all employees across the organization.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Security awareness means understanding that there is the potential for some people to deliberately or accidentally steal, damage, or misuse the data that is stored within a company's computer systems and throughout its organization.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Therefore, it would be prudent to support the assets of the institution (information, physical, and personal) by trying to stop that from happening.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] "The focus of Security Awareness consultancy should be to achieve a long term shift in the attitude of employees towards security, whilst promoting a cultural and behavioural change within an organisation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Modern security awareness programs increasingly utilize gamification, phishing simulations, and interactive learning modules.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Studies have shown that engaging employees through serious games, reward systems, and real-world attack simulations improves retention and application of security practices.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] One example is phishing simulation training, where employees receive simulated phishing emails to test their ability to recognize threats.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Research indicates that repeated exposure to such exercises leads to long-term improvements in security awareness.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] In a 2016 study, researchers developed a method of measuring security awareness.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Specifically they measured "understanding about circumventing security protocols, disrupting the intended functions of systems or collecting valuable information, and not getting caught" (p.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] The researchers created a method that could distinguish between experts and novices by having people organize different security scenarios into groups.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Experts will organize these scenarios based on centralized security themes where novices will organize the scenarios based on superficial themes.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Security awareness is also assessed through real-time security metrics, such as tracking phishing click rates, password reuse tendencies, and policy adherence rates.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] Organizations are adopting continuous monitoring strategies to provide immediate feedback to employees about risky behavior and suggest corrective actions.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/security-awareness] As cyber threats continue to evolve, security awareness programs must adapt to new attack vectors, such as AI-driven cyberattacks, deepfakes, and insider threats.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] In the context of information security, **social engineering** is the use of psychological pressure to influence people to perform actions or divulge confidential information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Phishing is a type of social engineering.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Researchers have developed detection techniques and cybersecurity educational programs.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Researchers in 2019 and 2020 said that social engineering was an increasingly important challenge for organizations and countries.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Reports indicated that through 2024, social engineering attacks had increased in intensity and number.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Social engineering techniques are based on weaknesses in human decision-making known as cognitive biases.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Social engineering is a form of psychological manipulation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] An example of social engineering would be an attacker who walks into a building and posts an official-looking announcement to the company bulletin that says the telephone number for the help desk has changed.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] When employees call the false number for help, the individual asks them for their passwords and IDs, thereby gaining access to the company's private information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Another example of social engineering would be a hacker contacting the target on a social networking site and starting a conversation with them.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Gradually, the hacker gains the trust of the target and then uses that trust to gain access to sensitive information like password or bank account details.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Pretexting, also known in the UK as blagging, is the act of creating and using an invented scenario (the pretext) to engage a targeted victim in a manner that increases the chance the victim will divulge information or perform actions that would be unlikely in ordinary circumstances.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] An elaborate lie, it most often involves some prior research or setup and the use of this information for impersonation (*e.g.*, date of birth, Social Security number, last bill amount) to establish legitimacy in the mind of the target.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Water holing is a targeted social engineering strategy that capitalizes on the trust users have in websites they regularly visit.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The victim feels safe to do things they would not do in a different situation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] A wary person might, for example, purposefully avoid clicking a link in an unsolicited email, but the same person would not hesitate to follow a link on a website they often visit.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] So, the attacker prepares a trap for the unwary prey at a favored watering hole.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] This strategy has been successfully used to gain access to some (supposedly) very secure systems.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Baiting is a form of real-world Trojan horse that uses physical media and relies on the curiosity or greed of the victim.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] In this attack, attackers leave malware-infected floppy disks, CD-ROMs, or USB flash drives in locations people will find them (bathrooms, elevators, sidewalks, parking lots, etc.), give them legitimate and curiosity-piquing labels, and wait for victims.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Unless computer controls block infections, insertion compromises PCs "auto-running" media.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] For instance, a "lucky winner" is sent a free digital audio player compromising any computer it is plugged to.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] A "road apple" (the colloquial term for horse manure, suggesting the device's undesirable nature) is any removable media with malicious software left in opportunistic or conspicuous places.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] It may be a CD, DVD, or USB flash drive, among other media.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Curious people take it and plug it into a computer, infecting the host and any attached networks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Again, hackers may give them enticing labels, such as "Employee Salaries" or "Confidential".
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] One study published in 2016 had researchers drop 297 USB drives around the campus of the University of Illinois.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The drives contained files on them that linked to webpages owned by the researchers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The researchers were able to see how many of the drives had files on them opened, but not how many were inserted into a computer without having a file opened.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Of the 297 drives that were dropped, 290 (98%) of them were picked up and 135 (45%) of them "called home".
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Ad phishing is a social engineering technique in which malicious actors use online ads to deceive users into believing they are interacting with legitimate brands or services.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] According to Google, these deceptive ads often mimic trusted entities such as banks, software providers, or customer support pages, leading users to fraudulent sites that attempt to steal passwords, credit card information, or other sensitive data.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] An attacker offers to provide sensitive information (e.g. login credentials) or pay some amount of money in exchange for a favor.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The attacker may pose as an expert offering free IT help, whereby they need login credentials from the user.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The victim is bombarded with multiple messages about fake threats and alerts, making them think that the system is infected with malware.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Thus, attackers force them to install remote login software or other malicious software, or directly extort a ransom, such as offering to send a certain amount of money in cryptocurrency in exchange for the safety of confidential videos that the criminal has, as he claims.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] An attacker pretends to be a company employee or other person with access rights in order to enter an office or other restricted area.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Deception and social engineering tools are actively used.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] For example, the intruder pretends to be a courier or loader carrying something in his hands and asks an employee who is walking outside to hold the door, gaining access to the building.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] In common law, pretexting is an invasion of privacy tort of appropriation.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The 1999 Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act (GLBA) is a U.S.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Federal law that specifically addresses pretexting of banking records as an illegal act punishable under federal statutes.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] When a business entity such as a private investigator, SIU insurance investigator, or an adjuster conducts any type of deception, it falls under the authority of the Federal Trade Commission (FTC).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] This federal agency has the obligation and authority to ensure that consumers are not subjected to any unfair or deceptive business practices.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The statute states that when someone obtains any personal, non-public information from a financial institution or the consumer, their action is subject to the statute.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] It relates to the consumer's relationship with the financial institution.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] For example, a pretexter using false pretenses either to get a consumer's address from the consumer's bank, or to get a consumer to disclose the name of their bank, would be covered.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The determining principle is that pretexting only occurs when information is obtained through false pretenses.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] In December 2006, United States Congress approved a Senate sponsored bill making the pretexting of telephone records a federal felony with fines of up to $250,000 and ten years in prison for individuals (or fines of up to $500,000 for companies).
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The Telephone Records and Privacy Protection Act of 2006 was signed by President George W.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The Florida-based company operates several Web sites that sell mobile telephone records, according to a copy of the suit.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The attorneys general of Florida and Missouri quickly followed Madigan's lead, filing suits respectively, against 1st Source Information Specialists and, in Missouri's case, one other records broker – First Data Solutions, Inc.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Several wireless providers, including T-Mobile, Verizon, and Cingular filed earlier lawsuits against records brokers, with Cingular winning an injunction against First Data Solutions and 1st Source Information Specialists.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Senator Charles Schumer (D-New York) introduced legislation in February 2006 aimed at curbing the practice.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The Consumer Telephone Records Protection Act of 2006 would create felony criminal penalties for stealing and selling the records of mobile phone, landline, and Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) subscribers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The law was passed at least partially in response to the Hewlett-Packard spying scandal.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Patricia Dunn, former chairwoman of Hewlett Packard, reported that the HP board hired a private investigation company to look into who was responsible for leaks within the board.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Dunn acknowledged that the company used the practice of pretexting to solicit the telephone records of board members and journalists.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Chairman Dunn later apologized for this act and offered to step down from the board if it was desired by board members.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Unlike Federal law, California law specifically forbid such pretexting.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The four felony charges brought on Dunn were dismissed.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Kevin Mitnick, Susan Headley, and Lewis De Payne were involved in phreaking and computer hacking efforts involving social engineering in Los Angeles in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The Badir Brothers, Ramy, Muzher, and Shadde Badir‍— all of whom were blind from birth‍— set up an extensive phone and computer fraud scheme in Israel in the 1990s using social engineering, voice impersonation, and Braille-display computers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] In 2011, hackers broke into the сryptographic corporation RSA and obtained information about SecurID two-factor authentication fobs.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Using this data, the hackers later tried to infiltrate the network of defense contractor Lockheed Martin.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The hackers gained access to the key fob data by sending emails to four employees of the parent corporation from an alleged recruitment site.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The emails contained an Excel attachment titled 2011 Recruitment Plan.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The spreadsheet contained a zero-day Flash exploit that provided backdoor access to the work computers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Department of Labor server was hacked and used to host malware and redirect some visitors to a site using a zero-day Internet Explorer exploit to install a remote access trojan called Poison Ivy.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Watering hole attacks were used, with the attackers creating pages related to toxic nuclear substances overseen by the Department of Energy.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The targets were likely DoL and DOE employees with access to sensitive nuclear data.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] On 24 November 2014, the hacker group "Guardians of Peace" (probably linked to North Korea) leaked confidential data from the film studio Sony Pictures Entertainment.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The data included emails, executive salaries, and employees' personal and family information.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The phishers pretended to be high up employees to install malware on workers' computers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] In 2015, specialized Wi-Fi hardware and software maker Ubiquiti lost nearly $47 million to hackers.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Attackers sent Ubiquiti's accounting department a phishing email from a Hong Kong branch with instructions to change payment account details.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Upon discovering the theft, the company began cooperating with law enforcement, but was only able to recover $8 million of the stolen funds, although they had hoped for $15 million.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] During the 2016 United States Elections, hackers associated with Russian Military Intelligence (GRU) sent phishing emails directed to members of Hillary Clinton's campaign, disguised as a Google alert.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Many members, including the chairman of the campaign, John Podesta, had entered their passwords thinking it would be reset, causing their personal information, and thousands of private emails and documents to be leaked.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] With this information, they hacked into other computers in the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, implanting malware in them, which caused their computer activities to be monitored and leaked.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Following the 2017 Equifax data breach linked to China's People's Liberation Army in which over 150 million private records were leaked (including Social Security numbers, and drivers license numbers, birthdates, etc.), warnings were sent out regarding the dangers of impending security risks.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] In the day after the establishment of a legitimate help website (equifaxsecurity2017.com) dedicated to people potentially victimized by the breach, 194 malicious domains were reserved from small variations on the URL, capitalizing on the likelihood of people mistyping.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Two tech giants‍— Google and Facebook‍— were phished out of $100 million by a Lithuanian fraudster in 2017.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The fraudster impersonated a hardware supplier to falsely invoice both companies over two years.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Despite their technological sophistication, the companies lost the money, although they were later able to recoup the majority of the funds stolen.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] There are several providers of training and education related to social engineering.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] In the 2000s, Mitnick collaborated on a training program for certified social engineering prevention specialists.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Christopher Hadnagy, an American information technology security consultant, has written several books on social engineering and cybersecurity.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] Department of Health and Human Services has identified social engineering, particularly phishing, as the leading initial attack vector in healthcare data breaches reported under the HIPAA Breach Notification Rule.
[src:social-engineering-awareness/social-engineering-security] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires organizations to implement a formal security awareness program that educates personnel about social engineering threats, including phishing and pretexting, upon hire and at least annually thereafter (Requirement 12.6).
